<div id="subtree-container" class="subtree-container"><div class="aea2d7dde423afa7ad9351a0886150a8-scss b51b00c1669ad99a1c607cd1e77c2824-scss" style="inset: 0px 269px 620px 0px; justify-content: flex-end;"><div class="afeebf1df237d4103108ba40799802d6-scss b174ef864cda601f37d52e9ca06b1dc7-scss"><div class="c13443431e58facf06f9d12490b92a82-scss" style="width: 90vw; max-width: 8.5in;"><div class="_0df5ec6b9902d7d22ccfa3ebb4f35211-scss">Identification Parameters</div><div class="e5e059a27f4c194020f0d961a3cb5989-scss" dir="auto"><div class="fr-view"><p id="isPasted">Models must include parameters for indicating element identification codes specific to that project, in order to relate the cost structure with model elements. &nbsp;</p>
<p>These codes are crucial for identifying elements and accessing information, therefore, they should cover the cost structure not only during estimation and project phases but also during facility management (FM) and asset management phases.&nbsp;</p>
<p>This ensures a consistent understanding of the unique identification code across Bills of Quantities (BoQ), specification documents, and any form of drawing tagging. Examples of such codes are Omniclass,<a href="https://icms-coalition.org/the-standard/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"></a> Uniclass, Masterformat and other project-specific or country-specific codes.</p>
<p>The chosen codification should be determined in the project EIR.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The specific placement of this parameter can vary based on the authoring software and quantification tools being used.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The element identification parameter should be defined in the EIR according to project requirements.&nbsp;</p>
<p>When setting identification parameters, you should consider the following:</p>
<ul class="decimal_type"><li>
<strong>MEP and Structural elements&nbsp;</strong>should use instance identification parameters. This is necessary because the same class or type of elements may be used across different systems, requiring unique codes. For instance, PVC pipes may be used in various systems but should be assigned to the cost structure within the correct chapter.<ul><li style="color: rgb(95, 95, 95);">Codes structured by <u>System &gt; Material &gt; Diameter</u>:<ul style="color: initial;">
<li style="color: rgb(95, 95, 95);">Examples for Pipes:<ul>
<li style="color: rgb(95, 95, 95);">Hot Water Systems <strong>&gt;</strong> PVC <strong>&gt;</strong> 100mm</li>
<li style="color: rgb(95, 95, 95);">Sewage Systems <strong>&gt;</strong> PVC <strong>&gt;</strong> 200mm</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li style="color: rgb(95, 95, 95);">Examples for Concrete Beams:<ul>
<li style="color: rgb(95, 95, 95);">Foundation <strong>&gt;</strong> In situ concrete beam (with detailed spec.) <strong>&gt;</strong> 50 x 100cm&nbsp;</li>
<li style="color: rgb(95, 95, 95);">Superstructure <strong>&gt;</strong> In situ concrete beam (with detailed spec.) <strong>&gt;</strong> 50 x 100cm</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li></ul>
</li></ul>
<ul><li style="color: rgb(95, 95, 95);">
<strong>Architectural elements&nbsp;</strong>can use type parameters or opt for instance parameters to maintain consistency across all disciplines.<ul style="color: initial;"><li style="color: rgb(95, 95, 95);">The code should be structured by <u id="isPasted">Material Type &gt; Size &gt; Requirements that might impact cost (Fire Rate / Acoustic / Access Control)</u><ul style="color: initial;"><li style="color: rgb(95, 95, 95);">Examples for Doors/Windows:&nbsp;<ul style="color: initial;">
<li style="color: rgb(95, 95, 95);">Wooden door &gt; 900 x 2100 mm &gt; Insulation</li>
<li style="color: rgb(95, 95, 95);">Steel door &gt; 1200 x 2100 mm &gt; 60 min Fire Rate</li>
</ul>
</li></ul>
</li></ul>
</li></ul>
<p>Before proceeding with the quantification of the modeled elements, conducting thorough quality checks is crucial to ensure the accurate assignment of all codes and avoid quantification errors.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div>